## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Also removed** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown; dead code |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it's fundamentally unsafe — it could corrupt application state by interrupting code mid-execution (inside locks, during I/O, etc.).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout.
            // Task.Wait throws AggregateException on fault or cancellation.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload in new code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cooperative cancellation only.** Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation tokens don't force-kill work. If `work` ignores the token, it runs to completion in the background even after the caller gets a `TimeoutException`. For CPU-bound loops, the work must check the token:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() =>
{
    // ❌ Old pattern — just runs forever, no way to stop it
    while (true) { /* compute */ }
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ Pass the token through (async overload)
await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    while (!ct.IsCancellationRequested) { /* compute */ }
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**2. `Task.Run` vs `new Thread`.** `Task.Run` uses the thread pool — better for throughput, but avoid if `work` blocks for a very long time (it starves the pool). For truly long-blocking work, use `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`.

**3. Exception wrapping changed.** The original code threw `AggregateException` manually. `Task.Result` and `Task.Wait` already throw `AggregateException` on faults, so the behavior is preserved automatically. If you use `await`, exceptions are unwrapped — only the inner exception propagates.

**4. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → dead code.** Delete it. It will never fire in .NET 8, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` would throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` if reached.

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Sync (drop-in replacement for existing callers)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SomeExpensiveCalculation(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));

// Async (preferred for new code)
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

### TL;DR

`Thread.Abort()` is gone — replace with `CancellationTokenSource` + `Task.Run`. The fundamental model shifts from **forced termination** to **cooperative cancellation**, which means work must opt in to being cancellable. There is no .NET 8 equivalent that force-kills arbitrary code, by design.
